# Time Complexity

## Brute Force

* Number of subarrays = **O(n²)**
* Compare every pair = **O(n⁴)**

**Time Complexity:** **O(n⁴)**

**Space Complexity:** **O(n²)** (to store all subarrays)

---

## Optimal

* Build `leftMax` = **O(n)**
* Build `leftMin` = **O(n)**
* Build `rightMax` = **O(n)**
* Build `rightMin` = **O(n)**
* Scan all partitions = **O(n)**

Overall:

* **Time Complexity:** **O(n)**
* **Space Complexity:** **O(n)**

---

# Pattern to Remember

This problem belongs to a common interview pattern:

> **"Two non-overlapping subarrays" → Precompute the best answer on the left and the best answer on the right using Kadane, then combine them across every partition.**

The same prefix/suffix preprocessing idea also appears in problems involving maximum sum, minimum sum, maximum product, and similar "best subarray on each side" constraints.
